03664nmm a2200601Ia 9781479882830DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798828307 a10.18574/nyu/9781479882830.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548220  a(OCoLC)946725463  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0380302bisacsh04a306.822231 aZug, Marcia A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBuying a Bride :bAn Engaging History of Mail-Order Matches /cMarcia A. Zug. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere have always been mail-order brides in America—but we haven’t always thought about them in the same ways. In Buying a Bride, Marcia A. Zug starts with the so-called “Tobacco Wives” of the Jamestown colony and moves all the way forward to today’s modern same-sex mail-order grooms to explore the advantages and disadvantages of mail-order marriage. It’s a history of deception, physical abuse, and failed unions. It’s also the story of how mail-order marriage can offer women surprising and empowering opportunities.Drawing on a forgotten trove of colorful mail-order marriage court cases, Zug explores the many troubling legal issues that arise in mail-order marriage: domestic abuse and murder, breach of contract, fraud (especially relating to immigration), and human trafficking and prostitution. She tells the story of how mail-order marriage lost the benign reputation it enjoyed in the Civil War era to become more and more reviled over time, and she argues compellingly that it does not entirely deserve its current reputation. While it is a common misperception that women turn to mail-order marriage as a desperate last resort, most mail-order brides are enticed rather than coerced. Since the first mail-order brides arrived on American shores in 1619, mail-order marriage has enabled women to improve both their marital prospects and their legal, political, and social freedoms. Buying A Bride uncovers this history and shows us how mail-order marriage empowers women and should be protected and even encouraged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMail order brideszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMarriage brokeragezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMarriagezUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLAW / Family Law / Marriage.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479882830.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479882830423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479882830/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles